<h1>The Federal &amp; Government Nurse Hub &mdash; The Stability Path, Mapped</h1>
<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">Government nursing is the path nobody sells you in nursing school. Travel contracts have louder marketing and hospital systems have bigger sign-on bonuses, but federal and public-sector nursing offers a combination that is hard to assemble anywhere else: a pension in a profession that mostly abandoned them, employer retirement matching on top of it, loan forgiveness that actually pays out, union-scale job security, and &mdash; in the military's case &mdash; a tuition-free route to the highest-paying nursing specialty there is. This hub collects every guide on the site that touches the government path and puts them in one place.</p>
<div class="hero-note">
<strong>The honest tradeoff up front:</strong> government nursing usually pays less per hour than the private-sector peak, hires slowly, and moves at institutional speed. The guides below don't hide that. The case for the path is the total package over a career &mdash; pension plus match plus forgiveness plus stability &mdash; not the biweekly paycheck.</p>
</div>

<h2>The VA: the biggest nurse employer in the country</h2>
<p>The Department of Veterans Affairs runs the largest integrated health system in the United States and employs more nurses than any other single organization. VA nurses are hired under Title 38, a separate personnel system with its own locality-based pay scales, its own promotion boards (Nurse I, II, III), and a benefits stack &mdash; FERS pension, TSP matching, generous leave, and PSLF-qualifying employment &mdash; that compounds quietly for decades. The full guide covers the pay system, the boards, and the real tradeoffs, including the high-cost-of-living pay lag and the famously slow hiring pipeline.</p>
<ul class="hub">
<li><a href="va-nurse-pay-benefits-2026.html">VA nurse pay &amp; benefits</a> &mdash; Title 38, the Nurse I/II/III ladder, and the full benefits stack</li>
</ul>

<h2>The military route &mdash; including a free CRNA</h2>
<p>Military nursing is the most extreme version of the government trade: the highest obligations in exchange for the largest benefits. The standout is USAGPAN &mdash; the Army's anesthesia program &mdash; and the uniformed route to CRNA generally, where the military pays full tuition and a salary during school in exchange for a service commitment. For the right nurse, it is the only way to reach anesthesia with zero debt; for the wrong nurse, the obligation math is a trap. The guide walks both sides, including the recruiter-contract warnings.</p>
<ul class="hub">
<li><a href="military-crna-usagpan-2026.html">Military CRNA &amp; USAGPAN</a> &mdash; zero-debt anesthesia traded against a service obligation</li>
<li><a href="crna-career-hub-2026.html">CRNA career hub</a> &mdash; the civilian version of the same road, for comparison</li>
</ul>

<h2>The money engine: PSLF and the forgiveness stack</h2>
<p>Public Service Loan Forgiveness is the reason the government path can beat a higher private salary on total math. Ten years of qualifying payments while employed by a government or nonprofit employer, and the remaining federal loan balance is forgiven tax-free &mdash; and most hospital nurses at nonprofit systems already qualify without knowing it. For a nurse carrying six figures of loans, PSLF can be worth more than a decade of pay differentials. The guide covers qualifying employment, the payment-plan choice, and the paperwork discipline that separates nurses who get forgiveness from nurses who get denied.</p>
<ul class="hub">
<li><a href="nurse-pslf-guide-2026.html">PSLF for nurses</a> &mdash; who qualifies, the ten-year clock, and the paperwork that protects you</li>
<li><a href="nurse-money-hub-2026.html">Nurse money hub</a> &mdash; the rest of the financial picture: investing, retirement accounts, FIRE</li>
</ul>

<h2>Adjacent stability paths</h2>
<p>Two roles live near the government path and share its DNA &mdash; regulation-driven, institution-shaped, stability-first. Occupational health nursing is the closest civilian cousin to federal work: OSHA-driven, business-hours, heavily credentialed, and hired by both corporations and government agencies. House supervision is the in-hospital version of the institutional ladder, and government facilities hire for it too.</p>
<ul class="hub">
<li><a href="occupational-health-nurse-career-2026.html">Occupational health nursing</a> &mdash; the OSHA-adjacent, business-hours specialty</li>
<li><a href="house-supervisor-nurse-career-2026.html">House supervisor</a> &mdash; running the building on nights and weekends</li>
</ul>

<h2>Who this path fits</h2>
<p>The federal path rewards a specific temperament. If you are optimizing for the highest income in the next 24 months, travel contracts and private-sector ICU differentials win, and the <a href="travel-nurse-tax-hub-2026.html">travel nurse tax hub</a> is your shelf. If you are optimizing for the highest guaranteed floor over 25 years &mdash; pension, match, forgiveness, and a job that doesn't disappear in a hospital merger &mdash; the government stack is very hard to beat, and it pairs naturally with the slow-wealth approach in the <a href="nurse-money-hub-2026.html">money hub</a>. Many nurses split the difference: private-sector years early for income and acuity, government years later for the pension math and the schedule. There is no wrong order, but the earlier the federal years start, the more the pension and PSLF clocks work in your favor.</p>
<div class="callout">
<strong>One thing every nurse should do this week regardless:</strong> if you work for a nonprofit hospital and carry federal student loans, check your PSLF qualifying-payment count. Nonprofit employment counts toward the same forgiveness as government employment, and every month you don't certify is a month you might be leaving on the table. The <a href="nurse-pslf-guide-2026.html">PSLF guide</a> shows exactly how.</p>
</div>

